Problem Statement¶

The aim is to build a predictive model and predict the sales of each product at a particular outlet. Using this model, BigMart will try to understand the properties of products and outlets which play a key role in increasing sales.

Dataset Description¶

The dataset contains 8523 rows and 12 columns. Each row contains is a product and its description

2) Random Forest Regressor¶

In [60]:
def result(y_test,y_pred):
    print(f"MAE : {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)}")
    print(f"MSE : {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)}")
    print(f"RMSE : {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))}")

6) K-Nearest Neighbors¶

In [72]:
rmse_val_list = [] #to store rmse values for different k

for i in range(1,round(sqrt(X_train.shape[0]))):
    model = KNR(n_neighbors = i)

    model.fit(X_train, y_train)  #fit the model
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test) #make prediction on test set
    error = sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)) #calculate rmse
    #print('RMSE value for k= ' , i , 'is:', error)
    
    rmse_val_list.append(error) #store rmse values
    
print("The minimum error we get is ", min(rmse_val_list))
print("The corresponding K value is ", 1+rmse_val_list.index(min(rmse_val_list)))

The minimum error we get is  1283.4264940030494
The corresponding K value is  24

Random Forest Regressor, is the best model to use since it has the lowest Root squared mean error¶

Item MRP the sales maximizes the Outlet sales.¶

Outlet Type being SuperMarket or Grocery Store also depicts the Outlet Sales.
